			<Body>
				<Text Type="text">
					&lt;p&gt;If you follow the information trail through Wikipedia's &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stout"&gt;page about Stout beer&lt;/a&gt;, you find that what was known as Stout became a strong, dark beer in the 1800s:&lt;/p&gt;

					&lt;blockquote&gt;
					  &lt;p&gt;In the 19th century, the beer gained its customary black colour through the use of black patent malt, and became stronger in flavour.&lt;/p&gt;
					&lt;/blockquote&gt;

					&lt;p&gt;You can see from the &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mash_ingredients#Black_malt"&gt;article about mash ingredients&lt;/a&gt; that black patent malt is "barley malt that has been kilned to the point of carbonizing, around 200 °C." It is apparently called "patent" malt because the inventor was awarded a patent for it. &lt;/p&gt;

					&lt;p&gt;Sometimes, this malt is used to darken the colour of other beers.&lt;/p&gt;

				</Text>
			</Body>
